## First-Time Setup

When a user opens the repo for the first time, they may not have a `.designer` file yet. See `setup.mdc` for the full onboarding flow — it walks them through identity, team info, and getting started. If `.designer` is missing and the user asks to create a project or screen, prompt them to complete setup first.

## What This Project Is

This is a design prototyping tool. Designers create:
- **Canvas screens** — Static HTML/CSS files for UI ideation. No JavaScript.
- **Prototypes** — Interactive HTML/CSS/JS mini apps that feel like real features. JavaScript is expected.

There is no backend, no database, no framework. The tool itself is vanilla HTML served by Vite.

## Project Structure

- `data/projects/<project>/` — One folder per project. The **project id** is the folder name (e.g. `sample-app`).
- `data/projects/<project>/project.json` — **Project name and metadata.** Contains `name` (human-readable title), `description`, and optionally `createdBy`, `createdAt`. The app uses this for the project hub title, nav breadcrumbs, and page titles. When helping in a project folder, read this file to know the project's display name.
- `data/projects/index.json` — List of all projects (`id`, `name`, `description`, `createdBy`, `createdAt`). Home page cards use this. New projects need an entry here and a `project.json` in their folder.
- **Designer identity (`.designer` file)** — Each user has a `.designer` file in the repo root (gitignored). Created during first-time setup (see `setup.mdc`). Contains `name`, `company`, and `team` array:
  ```json
  { "name": "Ben", "company": "Acme Inc", "team": [{ "name": "Ben" }, { "name": "Sara" }] }
  ```
  Use the `name` field for `createdBy` when creating projects. The `company` field provides team context. The `team` array lists all team members. If `.designer` is missing, the user hasn't completed setup — prompt them to run the setup flow.
- `data/projects/<project>/screens/` — Static screen HTML files for the ideation canvas
- `data/projects/<project>/prototypes/<prototype>/index.html` — Interactive prototype
- `data/projects/<project>/prototypes/<prototype>/meta.json` — Prototype name/description
- `data/projects/<project>/prototypes/index.json` — Prototype list shown on project page (`id`, `name`, `description`, optional `device`)
- `data/design-system/components/` — Shared design system component HTML files
- `data/design-system/registry.json` — Category list + groups (order controls layout)
- `public/styles/shared.css` — Design tokens (colors, fonts, spacing, radii)
- `public/styles/ds.css` — Reusable component styles (cards, buttons, chips, tags, rows)

### Design System Page Layout

The design system page (`design-system.html`) uses an **infinite canvas**: main sections (groups) stack **vertically**; under each, sub-categories are laid out **horizontally** in one row so the canvas uses width. Layout is driven by `registry.json`:

- **`groups`** — order defines vertical order. Each group has a header, then a single horizontal row of section cards (its categories).
- **Categories** — each has `group`, `name`, and `components`. Optionally `"layout": "row"` so that section's components sit side by side.
- **Adding content** — add a category to a group; it appears as another card in that group's horizontal row.

## Critical Rules

> These rules apply in **consumer repo mode**. In **core repo mode**, you are a developer working on the tool itself — these boundaries do not apply (see "Context Detection" above).

1. **Stay in your project.** Only create or edit files inside the designer's current project folder (`data/projects/<project>/`). NEVER modify files in other project folders.
2. **Stay in your prototype.** If the designer is working on a prototype (`data/projects/<project>/prototypes/<prototype>/`), all work happens inside that prototype's folder. Never touch other prototypes or project-level screens.
3. **Never edit the tool itself.** Do not touch root-level HTML pages (`index.html`, `project.html`, `canvas.html`, `prototype.html`, `design-system.html`), `scripts/`, or config files. If the designer asks to change these, stop and confirm: "That would change the design tool itself — are you sure?"
4. **Never edit the design system** without being explicitly asked. The files in `public/data/design-system/` and `public/styles/` are shared across all projects.
5. **Use the design system.** Always use existing CSS classes from `public/styles/ds.css` and design tokens from `public/styles/shared.css`. Read both files before creating anything.

## Canvas Screens — Static Ideation

Files in `public/data/projects/<project>/screens/` are canvas screens.

- **HTML + CSS only.** No JavaScript. No interactivity.
- Used for quick visual exploration on the ideation canvas.
- Wrap in a container with standard background and max-width:

```html
<div style="padding: 16px; max-width: 390px; margin: 0 auto; background: var(--bg-0); border-radius: var(--radius-lg);">
  <!-- Screen content here -->
</div>
```

## Prototype Mode — Interactive Features

Files in `public/data/projects/<project>/prototypes/<prototype>/` are interactive prototypes.

### How to detect prototype mode

The designer is in prototype mode when the file path matches `data/projects/*/prototypes/*`.

### What a prototype is

A prototype is a **self-contained interactive mini web app**. It lives in a single `index.html` (or a small set of files in the same folder). The designer prompts you to build it, and it handles its own:
- Form state (inputs, validation, error messages)
- Navigation between views/steps (tabs, multi-step flows)
- Animations and transitions
- Conditional rendering (show/hide based on state)
- Any interactive behavior that makes it feel like a real app feature

### Rules for prototype mode

1. **Read context first.** Read `meta.json` in the prototype folder to understand the prototype's name and purpose.
2. **Ask device type before building new prototypes.** When creating a new prototype (or if unclear), ask: "Should this prototype be mobile, desktop, or responsive?" Save the answer as `device` in `data/projects/<project>/prototypes/index.json`.
3. **JavaScript is expected.** Prototypes are interactive — write real JS for state, transitions, validation, etc.
4. **Use the design system.** Import styles in the prototype HTML using relative paths: `<link rel="stylesheet" href="../../../../../styles/shared.css">` and `<link rel="stylesheet" href="../../../../../styles/ds.css">` (5 levels up from `public/data/projects/<project>/prototypes/<proto>/`). Use tokens and component classes as the foundation.
5. **Add new styles inline.** If the designer asks for something not in the design system, use `<style>` blocks inside the prototype. Keep the shared design system files untouched.
6. **Self-contained.** Everything the prototype needs goes in its folder. No external npm packages or CDN scripts unless the designer explicitly asks.
7. **Look at the design system.** Read existing component HTML files in `public/data/design-system/components/` for visual patterns.
8. **One file preferred.** Keep the prototype in a single `index.html` unless it grows large enough to justify splitting.

### Example prompts a designer might give in prototype mode

- "Build a signup flow with email, password, and confirm password. Show inline validation errors."
- "Make a settings page with toggles for notifications, dark mode, and location sharing."
- "Create a search experience — type in a search bar, show filtered results below."
- "Build a multi-step onboarding: welcome, pick interests, set profile photo, done."
- "Add a bottom tab bar that switches between Home, Discover, and Profile views."

For each of these, you write the full interactive HTML/CSS/JS in the prototype's `index.html`.

## Design Tokens (quick reference)

- Backgrounds: `var(--bg-0)` (#ffffff), `var(--bg-1)` (#f8f9fb)
- Accent: `var(--neon-blue)` (#3b82f6), `var(--neon-teal)` (#06b6d4)
- Text: `var(--text)`, `var(--muted)`, `var(--muted-2)` (dark text tokens)
- Border: `var(--border)`
- Radii: `var(--radius-sm)` 10px, `var(--radius-md)` 16px, `var(--radius-lg)` 22px, `var(--radius-xl)` 32px
- Font: Plus Jakarta Sans (loaded via Google Fonts in shared.css)

## Available Component Classes

- **Buttons**: `.btn`, `.btn-primary`, `.btn-dark`, `.btn-sm`
- **Cards**: `.plan-card`, `.event-card`, `.ds-activity-row`, `.ds-interest-card`, `.ds-group-card`, `.ds-friend-card`
- **Plan carousel**: `.ds-plan-carousel`, `.plan-card-mini`
- **Event mini**: `.ds-event-mini-card`, `.ds-event-mini-grid`
- **Chips**: `.ds-chip`, `.ds-chip.is-active`, `.ds-chip-row`
- **Tags**: `.ds-tag`, `.ds-tag-tone-sunset`, `.ds-tag-tone-teal`, `.ds-tag-tone-green`, `.ds-tag-tone-mint`, `.ds-tag-tone-gold`, `.ds-tag-tone-dark`
- **Type pills**: `.ds-type-pill`, `.ds-type-plan`, `.ds-type-activity`, `.ds-type-event`, `.ds-type-place`
- **Avatars**: `.ds-recent-activity`, `.ds-recent-item`, `.ds-avatar-stack`
- **Section titles**: `.ds-section-title`, `.ds-home-header`
- **Plan rows**: `.ds-plan-row`, `.ds-plan-rows`
- **Form inputs**: `.form-group`, `.form-group label`, `.form-group input`

## Tone

> In **core repo mode**, speak technically — the user is a developer. Skip the simplifications below.

> In **consumer repo mode**, follow these rules:

- Speak simply. Avoid technical terms like "DOM", "component tree", "state management".
- Say "screen" not "page" or "route".
- Say "design system" not "CSS framework".
- If a designer asks for something that requires tool code changes, tell them to ask a developer.
- Be proactive: suggest design system components that fit what they're building.
